g freedom and excitement beyond traditional forms of art-making. While today the Fluxus collective is recognized for its radical neo-avant-garde works of performance, publishing, and relational art and its experimental, interdisciplinary approach, it was not taken seriously in its own time. With Fluxus Forms, Natilee Harren captures the magnetic energy of Fluxus activities and collaborations that emerged at the intersections of art, music, performance, and literature. The book offers insight into the nature of art in the 1960s as it traces the international development of the collective’s unique intermedia works—including event scores and Fluxbox multiples—that irreversibly expanded the boundaries of contemporary art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aArt, Moderny20th century. 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics)xHistoryy20th century. 0aAvant-garde (Music). 0aFluxus (Group of artists). 7aART / General.2bisacsh  a1960s.  aFluxus.  aavant-garde.  aconceptual art.  acontemporary art.  aintermedia.  anew media.  apostmodernism.  areadymade.  ascores.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069309640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226355085423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226355085/original  a978-3-11-069309-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles